<br>
I too was a pallbearer, when my grandfather died a few years ago. He died suddenly, in a car crash. He was as healthy as an ox. But at least I know that he knew how much I cared for him.<br>
<br>
While I was in high school, we had to write about the man we admire most. There was no question; I wrote about my grandfather. He was the most hard working, loyal, funny, down to earth man you could ever meet. I hope to be half of the man he was someday.<br>
<br>
His death affected me more than any of the others. My father's mother and father have both died. I never knew his mother, and his father I had only met twice.<br>
<br>
My cousin also died, a beautiful 7 year old girl, in a traffic accident. I still feel bad after all these years, because the last interaction I had with her was getting mad at her for spilling something on my suitcase when I was visiting.   <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
But the worst part about her death was that she was the 3rd child of my aunt to die out of the 6 she had.<br>
<br>
Also, my father died. He led a troubled life, but I was at least able to fulfill his wish of having his ashes spread over land and sea so hopefully he is finally at peace.<br>
<br>
So I guess the point is, sieze the day. Try to live life to it's fullest, and value friends and family. But try not to rue time not spent with loved ones when they pass. They know you care about them, and they are at peace. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#A62A2A>- </font><a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie>Firiona Vie</a><font color=#A62A2A> - </font><a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9>OT/OOC Forum</a> <font color=#A62A2A> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.246g<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

